The paper deals with coding theory and specifically with the Reed-Muller code, which is a well-studied topic in information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves algebraic-geometric codes, which are closely related to computational geometry, making cs.CG (Computational Geometry) a likely sub-category as well. The use of puncturing and list decoding suggests that the paper may also be relevant to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity). Finally, the paper involves the analysis of the rate and distance of the codes, which could fall under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
